        <h2>Independent Prison Oversight: Watching the Watchers</h2>
        <p>Now that Arizona has an Office of Independent Correctional Ombudsman, our work is just beginning. Our <strong>Independent Prison Oversight</strong> program trains directly impacted auditors to conduct parallel inspections of ADCRR facilities, ensuring the state office doesn't become a rubber stamp. We've developed an inspection framework covering medical care, use of force, grievance procedures, and conditions of confinement. In 2025, we identified facilities where the state oversight process missed critical suicide prevention failures.</p>
        <p>This program serves as rapid response. When incarcerated people report retaliation for filing grievances, our team—working with pro bono attorneys—files emergency motions, contacts oversight officials directly, and publicizes abuse within 24 hours. We're building a hotline connecting people inside directly to our advocates, bypassing ADCRR's monitored systems. This is oversight with teeth, powered by those who know every prison corner.</p>
        <p>Our goal is embedding community voice into state structures. We advocate for the Ombudsman's Office to hire majority directly impacted staff and publish findings in plain language, not bureaucratic jargon. SB 1507 gave us the skeleton; Praxis Initiative is building the muscle and nerve.</p>
