        <h2>Core Civics & ARTS in Prison: Developing Leaders</h2>
        <p>The <strong>Core Civics & Advocacy Training for Returning Citizens</strong> program is our leadership pipeline. Over 12 weeks, cohort members learn legislative process, media relations, public speaking, and campaign strategy. We provide stipends, childcare, and transportation because economic barriers shouldn't prevent participation. Graduates have testified 47 times before legislative committees, secured seats on the Governor's Reentry Taskforce, and launched grassroots organizations. This is how we transfer power to the next generation.</p>
        <p>Our <strong>ARTS in Prison & Think Motion</strong> program operates in multiple ADCRR facilities, serving incarcerated artists annually. Teaching artists—most formerly incarcerated—lead workshops in music, visual arts, dance, and movement. The work produced is stunning: last year's "Perryville Poetry Project" anthology sold copies with proceeds split between artists' families and our reentry fund. Beyond expression, these classes build analytical thinking, emotional regulation, and public voice—skills that translate directly to effective advocacy upon release.</p>
        <p>Together, these programs create a closed loop: art inside builds voice, training outside builds power, and both feed into our policy and oversight work. Every program amplifies the others. We're currently planning a 2026 exhibition, "Visions from Inside," featuring 50 visual artists at the ASU Art Museum.</p>
